# Given a filename, return the filepath. Default folder is the `data` folder in the current working directory.
get_path <- function(filename) {
  str_c(getwd(), "data", filename, sep = "/")
}

# Colors:
ISLR_blue <- "#176FC0"
ISLR_brown <- "#94340E"
ISLR_lightblue <- "#68A5DB"
ISLR_orange <- "#CC5318"

# Return vector of the names of numeric columns in a data frame:
numeric_cols <- function(df) {
  is_numeric_cols <- map_lgl(df, is.numeric)
  return(names(df)[is_numeric_cols])
}

# predict() function for regsubsets() as given in the book:
predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id,...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <- coef(object, id=id)
  xvars <- names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars]%*%coefi
}

Exercise 7

  (a)

View data:

Boston

Fit random forests on the data for a range of values of ntree and mtry:

set.seed(1)

M <- c(4, 6, 8, 10)
N.tree <- seq(5, 525, by = 5)

train <- sample(1:nrow(Boston), nrow(Boston)/2)

## List of random forests:
rfs <- map(M, function(m)
          map(N.tree, function(n) {
            if(n %% 100 == 0) print(str_c("m: ", m, "; n: ", n, " ..."))
            randomForest(medv ~ ., data = Boston[train, ], mtry = m, ntree = n)
            })
          )

## List of predictions for each random forest:
yhat.rfs <- map(rfs, function(rf_list) {
  map(rf_list, function(rf) {
    predict(rf, newdata = Boston[-train, ])
  }) 
})
#yhat.rfs[[1]][[1]] - predict(rfs[[1]][[1]], newdata = Boston[-train, ]) # test

## List of test MSE's for each random forest:
y.test <- Boston[-train, "medv"]
MSE <- map(yhat.rfs, function(yhat_list) {
  map(yhat_list, function(yhat) {
    mean((as_vector(yhat) - y.test)^2)
  }) 
})
#mean((yhat.rfs[[3]][[2]] - y.test)^2) - MSE[[3]][[2]] # test

# Generate matrix of MSE's:
MSE_matrix <- matrix(NA, nrow = length(N.tree), ncol = length(M))
for(i in 1:length(M)) {
  MSE_matrix[ , i] <- as_vector(MSE[[i]])
}

# Convert to long format for plotting:
MSE_df <- MSE_matrix %>% 
  data.frame() %>%
  set_names(as.character(M)) %>% 
  mutate(n_tree = N.tree) %>% 
  pivot_longer(cols = `4`:`10`, names_to = "mtry", values_to = "MSE") %>% 
  mutate(mtry = str_replace(mtry, "X", ""))

# Cache the results:
#saveRDS(MSE_df, "/home/brian/R/dir/ISLR_2/clean/data/MSE_df.RDS")

Plot the MSE for each value of mtry and ntree:

# Read in cached results:
MSE_df <- readRDS("/home/brian/R/dir/ISLR_2/clean/data/MSE_df.RDS")

colors <- c(ISLR_orange, ISLR_blue, ISLR_brown, ISLR_lightblue)
MSE_df %>% 
  ggplot() +
  geom_line(aes(n_tree, MSE, color = mtry)) +
  theme_bw() +
  scale_color_manual(breaks = rev(unique(MSE_df$mtry)),
                     values = colors) +
  labs(x = "Number of Trees", y = "Test MSE",
       title = "MSE for a range of values for mtry and ntree")

# Full data frame of tree data:
tree1_nodes <- data.frame(
  var = tree1$frame$var,
  n = tree1$frame$n,
  dev = tree1$frame$dev,
  yval = tree1$frame$yval,
  splits = tree1$frame$splits
) %>% 
  mutate(`cutleft (<)` = str_replace(splits.cutleft, "<", ""),
         `cutright (>)` = str_replace(splits.cutright, ">", "")) %>% 
  dplyr::select(-splits.cutleft, -splits.cutright)

# Extract the labels:
labels <- tree1_nodes %>% 
  filter(var != "<leaf>") %>% 
  mutate(label = ifelse(!str_detect(`cutleft (<)`, "[A-Za-z]"),
                         str_c(var, " < ", `cutleft (<)`),
                         str_c(var, "", `cutleft (<)`)))%>% 
  select(label)

# Replace the labels with the new ones that include the splits:
tree1_data$labels$label <- labels[[1]]

# Plot:

predict.regsubsets <- function(object, newdata, id,...) {
  form <- as.formula(object$call[[2]])
  mat <- model.matrix(form, newdata)
  coefi <- coef(object, id=id)
  xvars <- names(coefi)
  mat[, xvars]%*%coefi
}

Best Subset Selection

Use best subset selection and cross-validation (on the training set only) to select a model:

for(j in 1:k) {
  best.fit <- regsubsets(y ~ ., data=df[train, ][folds!=j, ], nvmax=r.max)
  for(i in 1:r.max) {
    pred <- predict.regsubsets(best.fit, df[train, ][folds==j, ], id=i)
    cv.errors[j, i] = mean((pred - y[train][folds==j])^2)
  }
}
mean.cv.errors <- apply(cv.errors, 2, mean)
p.min <- which.min(mean.cv.errors)

# Plot errors
data.frame(p  = 1:r.max, error = mean.cv.errors) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(p, error)) +
  geom_line(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(data = data.frame(x = which.min(mean.cv.errors), y = mean.cv.errors[which.min(mean.cv.errors)]),
             aes(x, y), color = ISLR_orange, size = 3) +
  labs(x = "No. of Variables", y = "CV MSE",
       title = "CV MSE for best subset selection")

Calculate the test \(R^2\) values:

# For RSS, R^2 can be calculated using 1 - sum((y[test] - ridge.pred)^2)/sum((y[test] - test.avg)^2). For MSE the below is used:
test.avg <- mean(y[test])

pls.test.r2 <- 1 - pls.test.error / mean((test.avg - y[test])^2)
test.r2 <- c(boosting = boost.test.r2,
             reg.best = reg.best.test.r2,
             ridge = ridge.test.r2,
             lasso = lasso.test.r2,

The logistic regression model has a missclassifiaction rate similar to the second boosted model (8.15% vs 7.12%). But it’s still worse than the null rate of 6.61%.

KNN

Perform KNN using the larger training set:

K <- 1:25
train.X <- as.matrix(df[train, -y])
test.X <- as.matrix(df[test, -y])
train.Y <- y[train]
test.Y <- y[test]
knn_11_preds <- lapply(K, function(x) knn(train.X, test.X, train.Y, k = x))

Plot the test error:

knn.error.rates <- sapply(knn_11_preds, function(x) 100 * (round(1 - mean(x == test.Y), 4)))
k.min <- which.min(knn.error.rates)

data.frame(k = K, error = knn.error.rates) %>% 
  ggplot(aes(1/k, error)) +
  geom_line(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(color = ISLR_blue) +
  geom_point(data = data.frame(x = 1/k.min, y = knn.error.rates[k.min]),
             aes(x, y), color = ISLR_orange, size = 3) +
  labs(x = "1/k", y = "Training MSE",
       title = "KNN Test Error")

Minimum error:

knn.error.rates[k.min]
[1] 6.61

KNN produces the minimum error with k = 9; the error is 6.61%. However, the model just predicts no purchase for every observation:

knn_11_preds[k.min][[1]] %>% as.numeric() %>% - 1 %>% sum() # knn preds are all zero
[1] 0

This means that the best KNN models is equivalent to the null model that predicts all zeroes:

knn.error.rates[k.min]
[1] 6.61
round(100 * mean(y[test]), 2) # null rate
[1] 6.61

This also means that the KNN model doesn’t correctly predict any purchases, since it doesn’t predict any purchases at all.
